## Git Commands

### git init

Initializes a new Git repository, creating a new `.git` subfolder in the current working directory.

### git clone [repository_url]

Creates a copy of a remote repository on your local machine.

### git add [file]

Adds a file or changes in a file to the staging area, preparing it for a commit.

### git commit -m "[commit_message]"

Records changes to the repository with a descriptive commit message.

### git status

Displays the status of changes as untracked, modified, or staged.

### git log

Shows a log of all commits in the repository.

### git branch

Lists all local branches in the repository.

### git branch [branch_name]

Creates a new branch with the specified name.

### git checkout [branch_name]

Switches to the specified branch.

### git merge [branch_name]

Merges changes from the specified branch into the current branch.

### git pull

Fetches changes from a remote repository and merges them into the current branch.

### git push [remote] [branch]

Pushes changes to a remote repository.

### git remote -v

Lists all remote repositories configured for the current repository.

### git diff

Shows the differences between the working directory and the staging area.

### git reset [file]

Unstages a file, or undoes changes in the working directory.

### git rm [file]

Removes a file from both the working directory and the Git repository.

### git tag [tag_name]

Creates a lightweight tag at the current commit.

### git fetch

Downloads changes from a remote repository without merging them.

### git remote add [remote_name] [remote_url]

Adds a new remote repository with a specified name and URL.

### git stash

Temporarily saves changes that are not ready to be committed.

